The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Business Briefs
                              
	 New Delhi, Dec. 16: Mangalore Refinery amp; Petrochemicals Ltd (MRPL) plans to borrow Rs 10,000 crore to expand its refinery and build a petrochemical plant in Karnataka. Sources said MRPL would borrow Rs 5,000 crore from ONGC and Rs 1,000 crore from the Oil Industry Development Board. The rest will be foreign loans. MRPL is increasing the capacity of its refinery to 300,000 barrels per day from 193,800 barrels at an investment of Rs 12,400 crore.                            
	 New Delhi, Dec. 16: The goods and services tax (GST) is unlikely to be introduced in the next financial year as the constitutional amendment to introduce it will take time to go through. It will be difficult to introduce the bill for GST in this winter session for certain difficulties (that) were reported to us, Asim Dasgupta, chairman of the empowered committee of state finance ministers, said.                            
	 New Delhi, Dec. 16: The government today approved a proposal by the Mauritius-based fund house, Indium, to invest Rs 2,500 crore in a fund managed by private equity firm India Value Fund.                            
	 Mumbai, Dec. 16: Italy today sought investments from Indian car makers and said it would encourage Tata Motors and Mahindra amp; Mahindra to take over Fiats unprofitable car unit in Sicily that is teetering towards a shutdown.                             
	 Mumbai, Dec. 16: Credit growth of banks remained quite low at just over 10 per cent for the fortnight ended December 4 on a yearly basis compared with over 20 per cent in the corresponding period last year.                            
	 New Delhi, Dec. 16: The Centre has revised upwards the rice production forecast by 2.2 million tonnes to 71.65 million tonnes for the 2009-10 kharif season.                             
	 New Delhi, Dec. 16: General Motors will display six production and concept vehicles at the auto expo here next month, besides putting on display its mini car Beat.
                                                                                                                          
